\pard\hyphpar0\widctlpar\sa120\sl240\slmult1\qr\i\f0\fs20\lang1033 Installed {\i0\fs22{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/pegasone/cov2con/tree/master/Windows" }}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1\cf2\ul\i\fs20 COV2CON}}}}\f0\fs20  version: 1.3.0\b\i0\fs24\lang4105\par

\pard\hyphpar0\widctlpar\sa120\sl240\slmult1 COVID-19 pandemic status indicators\b0\lang1033\par
\lang4105 The severity of a pandemic in a particular region of the world increases with its transmission rate, proportion of the population that is infected, and case fatality ratio; these characteristics can be estimated from publicly available pandemic indicators.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 The European Centre for Disease Control ({\lang1033{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en" }}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1\cf2\ul\lang4105 ECDC}}}}\f0\fs24 ) compiles public COVID-19 related data from multiple countries. The Our World in Data ({\lang1033{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ourworldindata.org/" }}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1\cf2\ul\lang4105 OWID}}}}\f0\fs24 ) group repackages the data along with information parsed from additional official sources. The Johns Hopkins University ({\lang1033{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/" }}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1\cf2\ul\lang4105 JHU}}}}\f0\fs24 ) makes its own data sets publicly available. These data should be interpreted with caution when trying to compare the severity status, or condition, of the COVID-19 pandemic across countries.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 COV2CON uses COVID-19 data sets published by OWID and JHU. The application is primarily designed to help visualize and explore the daily and historical values of three indicators that are considered to be most relevant for country comparison purposes: \b Positive rate\b0 , \b Total cases per million\b0 , and\b  Active cases per million\b0 . Here are the reasons why.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 For clarity, when a case is reportedly \f1\ldblquote\f0 confirmed\f1\rdblquote\f0  the patient has not necessarily presented with COVID-19 signs and symptoms that were confirmed by molecular tests (i.e., PCR). In many instances when cases are reported, only the molecular test was performed for diagnostic purposes.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 The number of new cases reported increases in proportion to the number of new tests conducted; thus, the new case count in a country on a particular date, while important to health authorities for resource allocation purposes is not a good measurement of the transmission rate of COVID-19. Instead, a better measurement is the proportion of new positive tests out of total tests conducted; this is the \b Positive rate\b0  indicator presented in the COV2CON application. However, it is a characteristic of the select population that took a COVID-19 test (because they had signs & symptoms, or have come into contact with a confirmed patient, or just volunteered to take the test), rather than of the entire population.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 Likewise, the total (or confirmed) number of cases increases with the number of tests conducted over a longer period of time. It is a cumulative count that does not factor in patients who recovered or died. However, a total case count that plateaus out is a good measure of how well a country controls the epidemic. To compare this effect across countries, the total case count is divided by the country population; this is the \b Total cases per million\b0  indicator presented in the COV2CON application and it is an estimate of the proportion of the population that \i has been\i0  infected.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 The active case count, which is calculated by subtracting recovered cases and deaths from total cases, is a good measurement of the COVID-19 burden in a country. Here again, for country comparison purposes it is divided by the country population; this is the \b Active cases per million\b0  indicator presented in the COV2CON and it is an estimate of the proportion of the population that \i is known\i0  to be infected.\lang1033\par

\pard\hyphpar0\widctlpar\sa240\sl240\slmult1\lang4105 Another indicator, which is used in some regions for travel restriction purposes, is new cases, or new cases per million or hundred thousand population, or a daily average variation of these. Because new cases increase in proportion to new tests, this indicator does not correlate with \b Positive rate\b0 , as demonstrated in the plot below for a country where new cases per million increased dramatically as more patients got tested while the positive rate remained low. Obviously, the severity of a pandemic does not increase just because more people get tested and consequently more cases are reported. For these reasons, the \b New cases\b0  indicator and variants thereof are not presented in COV2CON.\lang1033\par

