\pard\hyphpar0\widctlpar\sb240\sa120\sl240\slmult1\lang4105 Finally, the number of new deaths is difficult to interpret as patients who pass away in a hospital setting are generally tested for the Cov-2 virus if they came into contact with another patient who tested positive. If they do test positive, they count as deaths by COVID-19 although causality is not necessarily demonstrated. The same limitation applies to patients with comorbidities: it is very difficult to determine if the cause of death is the Cov-2 virus or the comorbidity. For these reasons, the \b New deaths\b0  indicator and variants thereof are not presented in COV2CON. \lang1033\par

\pard\hyphpar0\widctlpar\sa120\sl240\slmult1\lang4105 Experts estimate the average \i case fatality ratio\i0  (CFR) by COVID-19 to be between 1% and 2%, although it can be greater than 50% when comorbidities are present.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 Not all of these data are available for each country and for each date within the time frame since the COVID-19 pandemic broke out. For some countries, there are no \b Positive rate\b0  data available.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 As a confirmed case essentially means a PCR-positive case, these cases may continue to accrue until potentially all the population gets tested, especially in countries that have the means to do the testing. Therefore, it is not surprising to see active cases increasing with time in the developed world. A PCR-positive individual is not necessarily sick so this molecular testing methodon its own is a poor choice for evaluating regional COVID-19 status, and unfortunately it drives important decisions such as when and where to initiate lockdowns, restrict travel, close businesses, etc. Clearly we could use a better COVID-19 stick.\par
Meet the consolidated indicator \b ACPO-14\b0 , which stands for \f1\ldblquote\f0 Active & Positive 14 days\f1\rdblquote\f0 . It is computed as the square root of the product of the average \b Positive rate\b0  and the slope of \b Active cases per million \b0 over the last 14 days (where both data are available; slope computation allows for 1-2 days\f1\rquote\f0  worth of data to be missing at the ends of the 14-day sliding window but this is seldom the case, if at all) or zero, whichever is greater. It fits one possible intuition of pandemic risk. Feel free to ignore it or have fun with it. \lang1033\par
\lang4105 The idea behind \b ACPO-14\b0  is simple. Intuitively, the pandemic risk at a particular location increases with the positive rate and the density of active cases. If the positive rate drops to zero (i.e., there is no transmission) then it doesn\f1\rquote\f0 t really matter how many active cases there are as no more people will become infected. When the pandemic began, active cases were non-zero and the positive rate was high but the pandemic risk was still minimal as there were not many people who could transmit the infection. Last but not least, on any particular date \b Positive rate\b0  is a property of that point in time while \b Active cases per million\b0  is a reflection of the last six weeks of the pandemic, so together they describe a trend. Sounds ambiguous, ill-defined, and wishy-washy? Try experimenting with it and you may be surprised.\lang1033\par
\lang4105\par
\b How to use COV2CON\b0\lang1033\par
\lang4105 Upon launch, COV2CON will attempt to download over the Internet the most up-to-date data sets. If it fails, it will attempt to use previous, local data sets and you will be given the option to try a manual update later.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 Once the update is completed, the right-hand panel of the main application window shows a list of country names and values while the left-hand panel may show a graph of historical values for the selected country, if data is available.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 By default, the country list shows \b Total cases per million\b0  with country names sorted in descending order of the indicator values. You can click one of the four radio buttons in the toolbar at the top of the main window to switch between \b Positive rate\b0 , \b Total cases per million\b0 , \b Active cases per million\b0 , and \b ACPO-14\b0 .\lang1033\par
\lang4105 Note that countries for which no data is available on the date shown above the country list are included at the bottom of the country list, in no particular order, and instead of a value next to the country name the text \f1\ldblquote\f0 no data\f1\rdblquote\f0  is shown. However, if you click on one of these items, historical data will be shown in the graph, if available.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 To quickly find a country and its associated value, sort the items on the country list alphabetically (see below).\lang1033\par
\i\lang4105\par
Single country selection\i0\lang1033\par
\lang4105 You can change the selected country by using the Up/Down Arrow keys, or the mouse (click on the list and drag up or down).\lang1033\par
\lang4105 You can filter country names by typing in the text box above the country list. Double-click this text box to sort country names alphabetically in ascending order.\lang1033\par
\lang4105 While \b Total cases per million\b0  values are generally\lang1033  available for most country on any date, \b Positive rate\b0 , \b\lang4105 Active cases per million\b0 , and \b ACPO-14 \b0 (which depends on the last two) may not be available for the very last date or for some of the other dates. Simply change the date using the slider (see below) and the updated country name list will also include numerical values next to country names for the indicator currently selected.\lang1033\par

